29.1 We reiterated that Management thru the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Office to:
include in the LDRRM Investment Plan, the establishment of toilets for PWDs as well as an appropriate storage area in their designated evacuation center;
Establish alternative sources of water supply for the evacuation center;
Provide enough space for the community kitchen so that it can accommodate plenty of evacuees ; and
Establish breastfeeding area or lactation area.

The Local Chief Executive to:
1. Initiate the hiring of additional personnel under the Office of the Municipal Assessor relative to the staffing pattern applicable;
2. Require the Municipal Assessor to follow the process of tax assessment by following the assessment calendar as required in the Mass Appraisal Guidebook in order to implement general revision in a manner in consonance to the provision of Section 215 of RA 7160;
3. Revised the Tax Declarations subject of the audit effecting the changes as observed in audit and submit to the Auditor a certified copy of the revised TDs.;
4. Submit action plan to conduct a field inspection and verification in order to check whether there are other properties which might be misclassified, not declared, miscomputed, erroneously declared and unidentified.

LGU GAD Focal Point System:
1. Establish the LGU Database to be used in identifying gender gaps/issues;
2. Hasten the preparation of GAD Accomplishment Report to evaluate whether GAD PPAs of the LGU were effective in addressing gender gaps/issues identified.

1. The Municipal Engineer to fast-tract the implementation of projects implemented by Administration and to call the attention of the contractors of projects that remained uncompleted to facilitate completion thereof as soon as possible;
2. For projects that are physically completed, prepare the necessary reports as soon as possible and submit the same to the funding agency and request for inspection to this Office, together with its supporting documents to avoid delay in project inspection and technical evaluation by the Audit Team and COA-RTS; and
3. The Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant to monitor the contractors’ compliance with the contract period/ duration and take appropriate legal action against the contractor for delayed completion of the project including the possible imposition of Liquidated Damages.

Require the Municipal Mayor and Sangguniang Bayan and MEEDO, Municipal Treasurer and MPDC to:
• Make a comprehensive study on how to make the three (3) facilities operational and make it viable and responsive to the needs of the constituents;
• Enact an Ordinance regulating the Fees rate of the facilities;
• Provide adequate and trained staff/personnel to man the operations of the facilities; and
• Appropriate funds for repair and maintenance of the facility to maintain quality service to customers and general public.

It was recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Direct the Municipal Engineer to prepare and maintain a Monthly Monitoring Report to keep track of the progress of all PPAs within his power/jurisdiction from planning stage to implementation to completion since it is one of the duties of the Municipal Engineer to “administer, coordinate, supervise, and control the construction, maintenance, improvement, repair of roads, bridges, and other engineering and public works projects of the local government unit concerned” pursuant to Section 477 of RA 7160; 
Direct the Project Heads/Managers of all non-infrastructure PPAs to prepare and maintain a Monthly Monitoring Report; 
Direct the Municipal Engineer and Project Heads/Managers to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant on the costs incurred of the projects for inclusion in their respective Monthly Monitoring Report; and
Require the Municipal Engineer and other concerned officials to adhere strictly to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013.

Recommendation:

Require the MBO, MPDO, ICO-Municipal Engineer and OIC-Municipal Accountant to review the unobligated appropriations of completed proposed PAPs under the 20% EDF and the availability of such fund balances in the depository bank;

After determining the fund balances in the bank, and in order to maximize the utilization of related funds, consider the following courses of action:

Revert the unobligated/unexpended appropriations of completed projects for re-appropriation to other priority projects;
Require the MPDO to revisit the unfunded priority projects in the development plan or propose new projects for the consideration thereof in the re-appropriation of the unappropriated surplus;
Request the Sangguniang Bayan to pass the related resolutions on the budget to be funded from the unappropriated surplus for the specific priority projects for implementation; and
Execute without delay such projects which are determined to still address the present development needs of the intended beneficiaries.

